title: Stop locking the assembly files to msbuild tasks, same for xml docs.
body:
<!-- This is a template that helps us provide quicker feedback. Please use any relevant sections and delete anything you don't need. -->

### Issue Description
<!--
* Please include a clear and concise description of the problem.
-->
Currently msbuild locks the assembly files to msbuild tasks, and xml doc files when building programs, even if the tasks is referenced via ProjectReference to provide testing of said build tasks instead of using nuget packages for them as it is dumb to create an nuget package for untested msbuild tasks that may or may not be broken, by doing such it has an 99% chance that build would fail because the compiler cannot output the msbuild task assembly to the output directory for specific target frameworks due to the fact that msbuild locks said task assembly instead of reading the assembly as bytes using ``File.ReadAllBytes()`` and then loading from the byte array so that way when muilding the task and lets say it outputs to the directory that msbuild is using it that build WILL then NEVER fail on that. Likewise with xml docs when you got multiple TFM's and all of which outputs xml docs they get outputted to the outside of the TFM directory inside of the output folder so then msbuild locks said file and then build fails because it cannot output to that xml docs file I also hit this issue 99% of the time as well.

### Steps to Reproduce
<!--
* Include as much of the following as possible:

* A minimal sample project that reproduces the issue.
* Your zipped project.
* IDE / CLI steps to create the project and reproduce the behaviour.
* Your command line invocation
-->
command line (Works on Windows only):
```ps
git clone --recursive https://github.com/Elskom/Sdk
cd Sdk
dotnet build --configuration Release > trash.log // first time ignore the output because the build task for some reason is not attempted to being built 1st despite being ProjectReferenced and set to not reference the assembly output because of it being an msbuild task might be a regression somewhere or another bug.
del trash.log
dotnet build --configuration Release // now this you cannot ignore.
```

### Expected Behavior
<!--
* The expected output or behavior.
-->
For build to succeed on the building of the msbuild task despite being used with ProjectReference, and for the xml docs to not fail generation.

### Actual Behavior
<!--
* The actual output or behavior.
-->
Build can fail even when prebuilding the msbuild task assemblies because of msbuild locking the files indefinitely until you manually terminate the .NET Host. Same with xml doc generation on those files being locked so then nothing can open them or write to them (the compiler or w/e).

### Analysis
<!--
* If you have an idea where the problem might lie, let us know that here.
* Please include any pointers to code, relevant changes, or related issues you know of.
-->
I think the locking of the msbuild tasks is related possibly to the locking of the xml docs but not entirely sure. Funny thing is it seems to not happen most of the time when ran under github actions but happens on my pc with the failures of the task building or the xml doc generations.

### Versions & Configurations
<!--
* In a Visual Studio developer command prompt, run `msbuild -version` and paste the output here.
* If applicable, include the version of the tool that invokes MSBuild (Visual Studio, dotnet CLI, etc):

* Post any other relevant configuration settings here.
*   OS, architecture, etc.
-->
Windows 10 latest insider dev channel build (x64).
I am using .NET SDK 5.0.102 and that version of MSBuild

Can you clarify what you expect in the failure case? I tried your repro and got 72 warnings but no errors.
I'm wondering if your problem could be resolved with setting the environment variable MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE to 1, but I would guess (with little evidence) that the ideal solution would be to ensure your custom tasks are each running in their own task factory. As a particularly bad workaround, you could probably append /m:1...

@Forgind it can happen easily when there are any changes made (after a build with a clean tree on the git, after a commit, or after a pull from the remote that adds commits).

As a particularly bad workaround, you could probably append /m:1...

So basically you are saying to rewrite it inline but the issue is, it's also used on multiple projects (every one of them).

You can set the TaskFactory without inlining it. https://github.com/rainersigwald/build-task-in-solution-demo (specifically https://github.com/rainersigwald/build-task-in-solution-demo/blob/17508937bb9edb0b817820146f85adf0da331515/Task/DemoFunctionality.targets#L10) might help. It demos how to build a task in a TaskHostFactory so it can easily be reused by several projects but also doesn't lock the assembly after it's finished.

Also, would you mind clarifying the failure you saw, since I didn't see it?

It was because of msbuild being a long lived process and I was not using a factory 🤣.

Also happened because I had at times multiple (19) TFM's on a project, of which also outputs documentations and contained csproj hacks to force add the generated reference assemblies along with the copy of the docs inside of it's nuget package ref folder specific to each TFM I targeted (which if you have muitiple P2P references could generate an failure due to the docs being locked.

``C:\Program Files\dotnet\sdk\5.0.102\Microsoft.Common.CurrentVersion.targets(4394,5): error MSB3027: Could not copy "obj\Release\netstandard2.1\GitBuildInfo.dll" to "bin\Any CPU\Release\netstandard2.1\GitBuildInfo.dll". Exceeded retry count of 10. Failed.  [C:\Users\User\Desktop\github\MyPackages\GitBuildInfo\GitBuildInfo.csproj]``

Which also can happen on the docs with:
``C:\Program Files\dotnet\sdk\5.0.102\Microsoft.Common.CurrentVersion.targets(4394,5): error MSB3027: Could not copy "obj\Release\BlowFish.xml" to "bin\Any CPU\Release\netstandard2.1\BlowFish.xml". Exceeded retry count of 10. Failed.  [C:\Users\User\Desktop\github\MyPackages\BlowFish\BlowFish.csproj]``

I have since reduced the TFM's and also changed the task to Inline inside of a targets file too (However that does cause issue again because then dependabot now refuses to update packages inside of the props file which is then installed when someone installs the package).
